3a611003-de70-47ab-b1e9-af10950bb4c5.0b121b32-91bd-43f0-8f36-8c7bc642fba5.prompt=Username Of Host\: 3a611003-de70-47ab-b1e9-af10950bb4c5.0df369f5-ca09-444e-b1a7-2f55808287f4.description=
This flow uses a trace route to attempt to localize a network failure.

Note\: if a route cannot be found, it will take a long time to enumerate each hop. If this happens at the beginning of the trace route, the trace route may time out with a 500 server error. In this case, decrease the maxhops count.

Inputs\:
target - The host to traceroute to.
host - The host to traceroute from.
username - credentials for host.
password - credentials for host.
protocol - the protocol used to run the command (ssh, Telnet, WMI or local)
notifyMethod - How the user should be informed of the diagnostic's output.
remoteOS - if running a command on a remote host, what is the OS of the remote host (supported\: WINDOWS, LINUX, SOLARIS)
usernamePrompt - the prompt that when seen should send the username (required only for Telnet)
passwordPrompt - the prompt that when seen should send the password (required only for Telnet)
hops - The maximum number of hops to traceroute over.
hopTimeThreshold - The maximum amount of acceptable time between hops.
timeout - the timeout in milliseconds
keyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.
diagnostic so far - The diagnostic so far, used for chaining diagnostics.

Responses\:
success - The operation was successful.
failure - something went wrong.

Returns\:
A human readable diagnostic (updated diagnostic so far)

Inputs\: keyName - the key to check Responses\: isNull - if the key is a null pointer. notNull - if some value is stored in the key. 3a611003-de70-47ab-b1e9-af10950bb4c5.462adc2a-3ad4-461c-8cf3-19eb3b273441.prompt=Threshold For Maximum Acceptable Average Latency\: 3a611003-de70-47ab-b1e9-af10950bb4c5.58ac0046-0945-4eeb-9414-969df1bea11e.description=
Runs a Ping command either locally or remotely depending on the specified protocol. Credentials and other inputs (remoteOS, hostname, username, password, keyFile etc) are required if the command must be run from a remote host. The Telnet protocol also requires inputs for usernamePrompt and passwordPrompt. 

Inputs\:
    hostname - Hostname or IP address of the host computer where the Ping command will be executed.
    username - A username to authenticate to the host computer. 
    password - The password for the user account.
    targetHost - Hostname or IP address of the target host computer.
    protocol  - The protocol used to run the command.
Valid values\: local, ssh, Telnet
    packetSize - The size of the ping packet.
    packetCount - The number of ping packets to send.
    remoteOS - The operating system of the host computer (WINDOWS, LINUX, SOLARIS only are supported), if Ping is running on a remote host.
    usernamePrompt - The username prompt seen while using Telnet protocol. This input is required when Telnet protocol is used. For example, login\:.
    passwordPrompt - The password prompt seen while using Telnet protocol. This input is required when Telnet protocol is used. For example, password\:.
    keyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.
    timeout - The timeout in miliseconds for the Ping operation. Default is 90000.

Responses\:
    success - The command executed successfully.
    failure - The command could not be executed or had a problem during execution.

Returns\:
    packetsSent - The number of packets sent.
    packetsReceived - The number of packets received.
    percentagePacketsLost - The percentage of packets lost.
    transmissionTimeMin - Minimum time taken for transmitting the packet.
    transmissionTimeMax - Maximum time taken for transmitting the packet.
    transmissionTimeAvg - Average time taken for transmitting the packet.
    returnResult - Raw output of the command.
    returnCode - Return code of the executed command.
    error - The STDERR of the command.
3a611003-de70-47ab-b1e9-af10950bb4c5.604a800c-6b6f-4463-9476-51801b609a4a.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults".

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

Responses\: success - The user was notified. failure - Notification failed. 3a611003-de70-47ab-b1e9-af10950bb4c5.c76c8425-caac-44fa-913a-5415ad6bc205.prompt=Here is your diagnostic for ${host} 3a611003-de70-47ab-b1e9-af10950bb4c5.cd3b1959-4703-40a2-82db-1213a308bb91.prompt=${diagnostic so far} 3a611003-de70-47ab-b1e9-af10950bb4c5.d58e6a22-60d4-47f7-a3c0-d0a5a3c7ac84.transition.description=ping latency was ${latency}. 3a611003-de70-47ab-b1e9-af10950bb4c5.description=
Checks to see whether or not a connection exists. If it exists, checks to see if it is reliable. If it is problematic, checks the problems in the connection.

Inputs\:
    target - The host to ping
    host - The host to ping from
    username - Username for the host 
    password - Password for the host
    protocol - The protocol used to run the command (SSH, Telnet, WMI or local)
    notifyMethod - The method to use to report the diagnostic
    lossThreshold - The percentage of packet loss considered as acceptable for this connection
    latencyThreshold - The time (in milliseconds) considered as an acceptable latency for this connection
    remoteOS - When running a command on a remote host, the operating systesm of the remote host (Windows, Linux or Solaris)
    usernamePrompt - The prompt used to send the username (required only for Telnet)
    passwordPrompt - The prompt used to send the password (required only for Telnet)
    maxHops - The maximum number of hops traceroute diagnostic is allowed to descend
    timeout - Timeout in milliseconds
    keyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.
    diagnostic so far - The result of previous diagnosis, used for chaining

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully
    diagnosed - Problems found

Results\:
average latency - The average ping response time in milliseconds
% Packet Loss - The percentage of packets that ping replies were received for

Recommended Thresholds\:
Connection Type		Loss Threshold (%)	Latency Threshold (ms)
DSL modem			2		200
Cable modem		2		200
Dialup modem		2		500
ISDN Line			2		150
T1/T3/OCR			2		80
10 ethernet			2		10
Wireless			2		600
